<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> What game do I want to play<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.88)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2090'>Scott "CategoryOneGame" Church</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2090&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 28, 2007</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> What Game do I want to play?<br />
<br />
This is a question I&#39;ve been asking myself a lot recently so I&#39;m going to share with you some of the things that go into my decisions.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Many gamers usually start with one game that gets them into the card game world.  Those gamers usually get bored of that one game or they will see other gamers at local shops or at events and start wondering what the games they are playing are like.  Maybe you got into a game because a friend plays, it’s not as challenging anymore and so you want to move on.  Maybe you heard about this new game that has tons of prize support and you want to play it.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Well the first thing you should figure out is what you like.  Do you like miniatures, table top game or cards games?  Do you like games that have are hard to collect or do you want something where it’s all there to start out with?  Is the collecting aspect something that interests you?  Are you looking for a game that takes 10 minutes to play or hours to play?  How about if you want to play on a pro-tour or for money, or just play locally with your friends?  What does the company look like, is it going to go out of business in a year or change games on you?  Or is it something that has been around for years and has staying power?  Where am I going to get singles or boosters/boxes/starters?  Do I like the people I play the game with?<br />
  <br />
<br />
I’m probably like many of you out there.  You’ve been playing cards for most of your life.  You have played just about everything and You’ve gotten burned.  You have a lot less time to actually build and play games now so if You do play, You want it to be something You enjoy and something You want to do.  You want to play in something you can be ranked in, make money in, have friends in, not spend too much time or money on, and enjoy.<br />
<br />
<br />
So how do you get into a new game?  What’s the best way to do it?  <br />
Here are my tips to help you out.<br />
<br />
<br />
Go to a local gaming store.  See if you like the manager/owner, see what games are being played on their schedule and see if any interest you.  If so, show up the night of the event and see what it’s like.  Are people having fun, are their prizes, does it look like good competition.  Find a store you like and gamers you like, make friends and see if you can borrow a deck to learn how to play the game, see if you like it.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Do some research, go to the company’s website and see how long they have been making the game.  How many sets are out so far?  What will be your catch up level?  If it is someone like UD, go to different message boards and see what people are saying.  How did they treat their last product, did they kill it off because something else came along?  If it is based off of a product, see what the deal is with that product.  FullMetal Alchemist is a great game but getting into it now is a little late, there is basically only one expansion left and then the game is up in the air on where they go from there.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Find out where you can buy product, more and more gaming is becoming pocketed, is there anyone else in your state or area that sells the game?  If said store goes out of business, do you have anywhere else to play?  Is eBay your best bet for getting in new product, does the local store sell singles, do they sell product?  Are you going to have to fight with the store owner to get in the new set?  Does the store run the events or just some fan, what if the fan and store have a falling out, and who runs events then?<br />
<br />
<br />
Are you having fun, when you show up are you having a better time than staying at home playing video games or hanging with your family, is it worth your time to play this game?  <br />
<br />
<br />
Do you want to make money, Dreamblade, Magic and VS are all good ways to play at a high level and you can make money.  Just expect to lose your weekends and any chance at spending time dating or with family traveling each week.<br />
<br />
<br />
Is it worth the buy in charge or should you play a newer game that has less expansions out?  A game like Magic and Star Wars have years worth of cards that you probably haven’t seen, is it worth it to buy into an older game like this or to buy into something new like Ultimate Fighting System, World of Warcraft or Stargate.  <br />
<br />
<br />
If you get into a new game, how long will it stick around.  StarGate’s last season on TV is supposedly going to be next year, so does that mean the game will only last one year and then all interest will die.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Can you keep up with the amount of sets released each year?  VS basically killed itself by doing this as fans couldn’t keep up.  UFS puts out two sets each time every 3-4 months, can you handle the cost as well as the time sorting and thinking of new decks.<br />
<br />
<br />
When you get into a game, how do you want to do it?  Do you want to go slow and buy a pack here, a starter there?  Do you want to be good soon as you start and so you buy a huge collection or two off of eBay or a player in the area?  I’ve gone both routes here and I have enjoyed the slow route a lot more than I have the fast route.  Buying big collections can put you at the top quickly but you also miss out on the fun of buying a new pack, putting the best cards from it in your best deck and then letting it trickle down to your other decks.  I would almost say it takes the fun out of games when you just start out at top and not having to work your way there.  Right now I’m slowly getting into UFS.  It’s a lot of fun buying a starter or booster here or there and then learning how those cards fit.  It’s also a bit of an overload when you buy a big collection.  You also usually don’t get cards in all that great of condition with a big collection, other people might not take care of their cards like you would.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Well that’s a lot of questions you should think about when deciding to get into a new game.  <br />
<br />
With the current gaming market, here are the games that you are most safe investing big money into at this moment:<br />
Magic<br />
World of Warcraft<br />
<br />
Games that are fun to play but be careful how much money you spend<br />
UFS<br />
FullMetal Alchemist – depends on what happens after the movie set release<br />
A&A<br />
Star Wars and D&D Mini’s<br />
Stargate<br />
<br />
Games that if you have, it’s time to start doing something else<br />
VS<br />
Heroclix<br />
WWE Raw Deal<br />
<br />
Games that are fun that you can get on the cheap right now so they might be worth playing again or starting anew<br />
VS<br />
WWE Raw Deal<br />
Star Wars<br />
Star Trek<br />
LOTR<br />
<br />
<br />
Right now I’m looking for a new game. I’ve got burnt by almost every game maker or game I have played and I’m sort of sick of it.  I just started playing UFS and its fun.  I enjoy it, I’m not spending a ton of money on it.  I just bought my first box to go with my 4 starters and random promo’s I’ve picked up.  It’s a lot of fun taking it slow and enjoying the game.<br />
<br />
<br />
I’ve also started going back and playing those forgotten gems. I have tons of different games though just sitting in boxes.  So I&#39;ve started pulling them out.  Wildstorms was awsome, some of the local guys know how to play that. <br />
<br />
<br />
I’ve been organizing all my Star Trek cards and it’s amazing how much fun I had playing that game and all the good memories.  I’ve signed up to run States in Utah for it because I want to enjoy it, plus it’s cheap.  LOTR has also been something I’ve been playing again recently as a good group of players have popped up.  Star Wars will always be number one to me and is my most played and thought about game.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Sometimes getting into a new game is as easy as pulling out the ones you love, posting a tournament date and seeing what classic players show up.  <br />
<br />
<br />
